Monthly Trend on Sales and Profit (Line Chart)¶

In [7]:
# Set 'Order Date' as the index
df.set_index('Order Date', inplace=True)

# Resample the data to monthly totals using 'M' (month-start or month-end as needed)
monthly_totals = df.resample('ME').agg({
    'Sales': 'sum',
    'Profit': 'sum'
})

# Format the index to 'Month-Year'
monthly_totals.index = monthly_totals.index.to_period('M').strftime('%b-%Y')

# Plot the monthly totals as a line chart
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 6))

plt.plot(monthly_totals.index, monthly_totals['Sales'], label='Monthly Sales', marker='o', color='blue')
plt.plot(monthly_totals.index, monthly_totals['Profit'], label='Monthly Profit', marker='o', color='green')

# Add labels and title
plt.title('Monthly Sales and Profit') 
plt.xlabel('Month-Year') 
plt.ylabel('Amount') 
plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
#plt.grid(True)
plt.grid(axis='x')  # Grid only for the x-axis (vertical lines)

# Add legend and adjust layout
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout for better display
plt.show()

Sales and Profits Trend of Technology, Furniture, and Office Supplies¶

In [8]:
# Read the CSV file with proper encoding and date parsing
df = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/JQE9675M2SSD512/[DeskPy/GlobalSuperstore/Store.csv', 
                 encoding='ISO-8859-1', 
                 parse_dates=['Order Date'], 
                 dayfirst=True)

#encoding='ISO-8859-1': This specifies that the file should be read using the ISO-8859-1 encoding, 
#which supports many Western European characters that might not be supported in UTF-8.

# 'Order Date' is in string format
# Standardize the 'Order Date' column
df['Order Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date'], errors='coerce', dayfirst=True)

# Convert Sales and Profit columns to numeric (before resampling), in case they contain non-numeric values
df['Sales'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Sales'], errors='coerce')
df['Profit'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Profit'], errors='coerce')
df['Quantity'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Quantity'], errors='coerce')

# Extract month and year from 'Order Date' for grouping
df['YearMonth'] = df['Order Date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group the data by YearMonth and Category, summing up Sales and Profit
monthly_trends = df.groupby(['YearMonth', 'Category'])[['Sales', 'Profit']].sum().reset_index()

# Plot the trends for each category
categories = ['Technology', 'Furniture', 'Office Supplies']

for category in categories:
    subset = monthly_trends[monthly_trends['Category'] == category]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 6))
    
    # Plot Sales
    plt.plot(subset['YearMonth'].astype(str), subset['Sales'], label='Sales', marker='o', color='blue')
    
    # Plot Profit
    plt.plot(subset['YearMonth'].astype(str), subset['Profit'], label='Profit', marker='o', color='green')
    
    plt.title(f'Monthly Trend of Sales and Profit for {category}')
    plt.xlabel('Month-Year')
    plt.ylabel('Amount')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.grid(axis='x')  # Grid only for the x-axis (vertical lines)
    plt.legend()
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Sales Trend of Subcategories under their Respective Categories (Line Chart)¶

In [9]:
# Create a new column 'Month-Year' for easier grouping (YYYY-MM format)
df['Month-Year'] = df['Order Date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group by 'Category', 'Sub-Category', and 'Month-Year', and sum the 'Sales'
grouped_data = df.groupby(['Category', 'Sub-Category', 'Month-Year'])['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Get unique categories
categories = df['Category'].unique()

# Create separate line charts for each 'Category'
for category in categories:
    # Filter data for the current category
    category_data = grouped_data[grouped_data['Category'] == category]

    # Plot the sales trend for each sub-category in this category
    plt.figure(figsize=(30, 6))

    # Iterate over the sub-categories and plot each one
    for sub_category in category_data['Sub-Category'].unique():
        sub_category_data = category_data[category_data['Sub-Category'] == sub_category]
        plt.plot(sub_category_data['Month-Year'].astype(str), sub_category_data['Sales'], label=sub_category)

    # Add labels and title
    plt.title(f'Monthly Sales Trend for {category}')
    plt.xlabel('Month-Year')
    plt.ylabel('Sales')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Sub-Category')
    plt.grid(axis='x')  # Grid only for the x-axis (vertical lines)

    # Show the plot for the current category
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Sales Trend of Subcategories under Technology (Bokeh Line Chart)¶

In [10]:
# Filter the data for 'Technology' category and set 'Order Date' as the index
tech_data = df[df['Category'] == 'Technology']
tech_data.set_index('Order Date', inplace=True)

# Group by 'Sub-Category' and resample by month to sum the 'Sales' values
monthly_sales = tech_data.groupby('Sub-Category').resample('M')['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Get unique sub-categories
sub_categories = monthly_sales['Sub-Category'].unique()

# Choose a color palette (use a palette with enough colors for your sub-categories)
colors = Category10[len(sub_categories)]

# Create a Bokeh figure
p = figure(x_axis_type='datetime', title='Monthly Sales of Technology Sub-Categories',
           width=1000, height=400)

# Loop through each unique sub-category and plot its sales data with a unique color
for sub_category, color in zip(sub_categories, colors):
    sub_category_data = monthly_sales[monthly_sales['Sub-Category'] == sub_category]
    
    # Create a ColumnDataSource for Bokeh
    source = ColumnDataSource(data={
        'date': sub_category_data['Order Date'],
        'sales': sub_category_data['Sales'],
        'sub_category': [sub_category] * len(sub_category_data)
    })
    
    # Add line and circle markers for each sub-category with a specific color
    p.line('date', 'sales', source=source, line_width=2, color=color, legend_label=sub_category)
    p.scatter('date', 'sales', source=source, size=6, color=color)  # Circle markers shows warning message

# Add HoverTool for interaction (shows sub-category and sales value on hover)
hover = HoverTool(tooltips=[('Sub-Category', '@sub_category'), ('Sales', '@sales{0,0}')])
p.add_tools(hover)

# Configure the legend and axis labels
p.legend.title = 'Sub-Category'
p.xaxis.axis_label = 'Month'
p.yaxis.axis_label = 'Total Sales'

# Format the x-axis to display month and year
p.xaxis.formatter = DatetimeTickFormatter(months="%b %Y")

# Rotate the x-axis labels for better readability
p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 3.14 / 4

# Show the plot
show(p)

Total Categorical Sales (Tree Map)¶

In [12]:
import squarify  # for treemap

# Group by 'Category' and sum the 'Sales' values
grouped_data = df.groupby(['Category'])['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Define specific colors for each category
colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c']  # Assign colors for Technology, Furniture, and Office Supplies

# Create the treemap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
squarify.plot(sizes=grouped_data['Sales'], label=grouped_data['Category'], alpha=0.8, color=colors)

# Add labels and title
plt.title('Total Sales by Category')
plt.axis('off')  # Hide axes

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Total Categorical Sales (Donut Chart)¶

In [13]:
# Group by 'Category' and sum the 'Sales' values
grouped_data = df.groupby(['Category'])['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Create the donut chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

# Pie chart (donut chart)
wedges, texts, autotexts = plt.pie(grouped_data['Sales'], 
                                   labels=grouped_data['Category'], 
                                   autopct='%1.1f%%', 
                                   startangle=90, 
                                   pctdistance=0.85,  # To position percentage inside the donut
                                   wedgeprops={'linewidth': 2, 'edgecolor': 'white'})

# Draw a white circle at the center to make it a donut chart
center_circle = plt.Circle((0, 0), 0.70, fc='white')
plt.gca().add_artist(center_circle)

# Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle
plt.gca().set_aspect('equal')

# Add title
plt.title('Total Sales by Category')

# Annotate each wedge with the actual sales values
for i, txt in enumerate(autotexts):
    txt.set_text(f"{grouped_data['Sales'].iloc[i]:,.0f}")

# Display the plot
plt.show()

Total Sub-categorical Sales (Tree Map)¶

In [14]:
import textwrap  # for wrapping the text

# Group by 'Category' and 'Sub-Category' and sum the 'Sales'
grouped_data = df.groupby(['Category', 'Sub-Category'])['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

# Create labels in the format 'Category - Sub-Category'
grouped_data['Label'] = grouped_data['Sub-Category'] #grouped_data['Category'] + ' - ' + 

# Define a function to wrap text for each label
def wrap_label(text, width=20):
    return "\n".join(textwrap.wrap(text, width=width))

# Apply text wrapping to each label
grouped_data['Wrapped Label'] = grouped_data['Label'].apply(wrap_label)

# Assign colors to categories (optional but makes it visually more distinct)
category_colors = {
    'Technology': '#1f77b4',    # Blue
    'Furniture': '#ff7f0e',     # Orange
    'Office Supplies': '#2ca02c'  # Green
}

# Create a list of colors corresponding to each sub-category's parent category
colors = grouped_data['Category'].map(category_colors)

# Create the treemap
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
squarify.plot(
    sizes=grouped_data['Sales'],         # Sizes of each partition based on 'Sales'
    label=grouped_data['Wrapped Label'], # Use wrapped labels
    color=colors,                        # Use the color corresponding to the category
    alpha=0.8,                           # Transparency level
    edgecolor="black"
)

# Add title
plt.title('Treemap of Sales by Category and Sub-Category')
plt.axis('off')  # Hide axes

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Sales of Sub-categories in Different Markets (Column Charts)¶

# List of markets
markets = df['Market'].unique()

# Plot a separate chart for each market
for market in markets:
    # Filter data for the current market
    market_data = df[df['Market'] == market]
    
    # Group by Sub-Category and sum Sales
    subcategory_sales = market_data.groupby('Sub-Category')['Sales'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    # Create the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 3))
    
    # Bar chart
    plt.bar(subcategory_sales.index, subcategory_sales.values, color='skyblue')
    
    # Add labels and title
    plt.title(f'Total Sales of Sub-Categories in {market}', fontsize=14)
    #plt.xlabel('Sub-Category', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Total Sales', fontsize=12)
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    
    # Show the plot
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
